title: Gradient Forest
text: final stages data formatting needed compatibility running GF analysis. : Splitting taxonomic flow/environmental data separate datasets Selecting environmental variables want use modelling Splitting samples season Removing infrequently occurring taxa (<8 occurrences particular season), ensure sufficient number observations regression trees created. minimum value can adjusted (see ) never <5.
code: # split taxonomic and environmental datasets cs5_tax <- cs5_diat_all %>% select(SAMPLE_ID:`Fragilaria famelica`) cs5_env <- cs5_diat_all %>% select(c(SAMPLE_ID, biol_site_id: max_doy_lag0))  # centre sampling year variable cs5_env <- cs5_env %>% mutate(Year_centred = Year - 2012)  # select environmental variables to be used as model predictors cs5_env <- cs5_env %>%    select(c(SAMPLE_ID, Season, Year_centred, ALTITUDE, DIST_FROM_SOURCE, ALKALINITY, FINE_SEDIMENT,            Arable_extent, HMSRBB, Q10z_lag0, Q95z_lag0))  # refine variable names cs5_env <- cs5_env %>%    set_colnames(c("Sample_ID","Season","Year", "Altitude", "Dist_from_source", "Alkalinity",                   "Fine_sediment", "Arable_extent", "Resectioning", "Q10", "Q95"))  cs5_tax <- cs5_tax %>% dplyr::rename(Sample_ID = "SAMPLE_ID")  # split dataset by season  cs5_env_files <- split(cs5_env, cs5_env$Season)  # now get matching taxonomic dataframes for spring and autumn   cs5_tax_grp <- left_join(cs5_tax, cs5_env %>% select(c(Sample_ID, Season)), by="Sample_ID") %>%    droplevels cs5_tax_files <- split(cs5_tax_grp, cs5_tax_grp$Season)  # GF is regression-based so will struggle with any infrequently occurring taxa # here we remove all taxa with <8 occurrences to ensure a sufficient number of observations for analysis # we can remove the superfluous columns (sample ID and season) from the taxonomic data at the same time  # as we only want to retain the taxa columns  cs5_tax_files <- cs5_tax_files %>% lapply(., function(x) x[!(names(x) %in% c("Sample_ID", "Season"))]) %>%   lapply(., function(x) x %>% select(where(~ sum(. > 0) >=8)))  # we now have 85 diatom species for modelling of spring data and 94 for autumn  # the final step is to remove any superfluous columns from our environmental data cs5_env_files <- cs5_env_files %>% lapply(., function(x) x[!(names(x) %in% c("Sample_ID", "Season"))])

title: Gradient Forest
text: now ready run GF models. season specify relevant pair environmental taxonomic datasets. arguments gradientForest() function specify “ntree = 500” create random forests comprising 500 trees. specify “corr.threshold = 0.5” compute conditional rather marginal permutation order guard collinearity predictors, set correlation threshold 0.5. information arguments type ?gradientForest see https://gradientforest.r-forge.r-project.org/biodiversity-survey.pdf. Note function may take run large dataset. may also return warning message: “response five fewer unique values. sure want regression?”, case look increasing threshold used remove infrequently occurring taxa.
code: cs5_spr_GF <- gradientForest(data.frame(cs5_env_files$Spring, cs5_tax_files$Spring),                                   predictor.vars = colnames(data.frame(cs5_env_files$Spring)),                                   response.vars = colnames(data.frame(cs5_tax_files$Spring)),                                   ntree = 500, transform = NULL, maxLevel=2,                                   compact = FALSE, corr.threshold = 0.5)  cs5_aut_GF <- gradientForest(data.frame(cs5_env_files$Autumn, cs5_tax_files$Autumn),                                   predictor.vars = colnames(data.frame(cs5_env_files$Autumn)),                                   response.vars = colnames(data.frame(cs5_tax_files$Autumn)),                                   ntree = 500, transform = NULL, maxLevel=2,                                   compact = FALSE, corr.threshold = 0.5)

Note particular responses may based relatively occurrence records, main strength GF analysis deriving community-level trends aggregation taxon-specific responses. plots show abrupt changes spring abundance (steepest parts curves) response winter high flows similar across species, clustering close standardised Q10 value 0. autumn cumulative changes abundance response Q95 appear gradual, exception Denticula tenuis. might infer spring species responses winter high flows exhibit signs threshold behaviour, sensitivity even relatively low Q10 values, whereas autumn sensitivity declining low flows similar across gradient.
code: # extract cumulative importance of splits for each species cs5_spr_cumimp <- cs5_spr_GF$res %>% dplyr::mutate_at("spec", ~gsub('.', ' ', ., fixed = TRUE)) %>%    dplyr::filter(var=="Q10", spec %in% cs5_spr_sp_tab$Species) %>% dplyr::select(spec,var,split,improve.norm) %>%      dplyr::group_by(spec) %>% arrange(split) %>% dplyr::mutate(improve.cum = cumsum(improve.norm))  cs5_aut_cumimp <- cs5_aut_GF$res %>% dplyr::mutate_at("spec", ~gsub('.', ' ', ., fixed = TRUE)) %>%    dplyr::filter(var=="Q95", spec %in% cs5_aut_sp_tab$Species) %>% dplyr::select(spec,var,split,improve.norm) %>%      dplyr::group_by(spec) %>% arrange(split) %>% dplyr::mutate(improve.cum = cumsum(improve.norm))  # create plots cs5_spr_cumimp_plot <- ggplot(data=cs5_spr_cumimp, aes(x=split, y=improve.cum, color=spec)) +     geom_line(linewidth=1.3) + ggtitle("Spring") +     xlab("Q10") +     ylab("Cumulative importance") +      labs(color="Species") +   theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 12), axis.title = element_text(size = 12),         plot.title = element_text(size = 12), legend.text = element_text(size = 10))   cs5_aut_cumimp_plot <- ggplot(data=cs5_aut_cumimp, aes(x=split, y=improve.cum, color=spec)) +     geom_line(linewidth=1.3) + ggtitle("Autumn") +     xlab("Q95") +     ylab("Cumulative importance") +      labs(color="Species") +   theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 12), axis.title = element_text(size = 12),         plot.title = element_text(size = 12), legend.text = element_text(size = 10)) # plot cs5_cumimp_plots <- list(cs5_spr_cumimp_plot, cs5_aut_cumimp_plot) gridExtra::grid.arrange(grobs = cs5_cumimp_plots)

text: gradientForest package offers option combine multiple GF models single object purposes comparison. combine spring autumn models plot cumulative change abundance along flow gradients. comparison confirms relative lack significant diatom species turnover response summer Q10 autumn response winter Q95 spring. can also pick relatively gradual change autumn species composition varying summer low flows, contrasting much greater species turnover occurring spring response winter Q10. might conclude diatom species composition sensitive winter spates summer low flow events. nonetheless keep mind observations based relatively limited data (< 120 samples season), sensitivity testing flow windows.
code: # Combine GF models cs5_comb_GF <- combinedGradientForest(Spring=cs5_spr_GF, Autumn=cs5_aut_GF)  # format data for plotting # Q10 cs5_comb_GF_Q10 <- cbind(cs5_comb_GF$CU$Q10$Spring$x, cs5_comb_GF$CU$Q10$Spring$y,                                cs5_comb_GF$CU$Q10$Autumn$y) %>% as_tibble() %>%    magrittr::set_colnames(c("Flow", "Spring", "Autumn")) %>%   pivot_longer(!Flow, names_to = "Season", values_to = "Cumulative_Importance") %>%   add_column(Predictor="Q10")  # Q95 cs5_comb_GF_Q95 <- cbind(cs5_comb_GF$CU$Q95$Spring$x, cs5_comb_GF$CU$Q95$Spring$y,                                cs5_comb_GF$CU$Q95$Autumn$y) %>% as_tibble() %>%    magrittr::set_colnames(c("Flow", "Spring", "Autumn")) %>%   pivot_longer(!Flow, names_to = "Season", values_to = "Cumulative_Importance") %>%   add_column(Predictor="Q95")  # combine cs5_season_comp <- rbind(cs5_comb_GF_Q10, cs5_comb_GF_Q95) cs5_season_comp$Predictor <- factor(cs5_season_comp$Predictor, levels = c("Q10", "Q95")) cs5_season_comp$Season <- factor(cs5_season_comp$Season, levels = c("Spring", "Autumn")) # plot cs5_season_comp %>%   ggplot(aes(Flow, Cumulative_Importance, color=Season)) + geom_line(linewidth=1.2) +    facet_grid(~Predictor) +    xlim(-2, 4) +   theme(axis.title = element_text(size=14), axis.text = element_text(size = 12),   strip.text = element_text(size=14), legend.text = element_text(size=10)) +   scale_color_manual(values=c("palegreen3", "goldenrod1"))

title: Vignette
text: hetoolkit package comprises collection 21 functions assembling, processing, visualising modelling hydro-ecological data. : import_nrfa importing flow data National River Flow Archive (NRFA); import_hde importing flow data Environment Agency (EA) Hydrology Data Explorer (HDE); import_flowfiles importing flow data local files; import_flow importing flow data mix sources; impute_flow infilling missing records daily flow time series one sites (gauging stations) using either interpolation equipercentile method. import_inv importing macroinvertebrate sampling data EA Ecology Fish Data Explorer; import_env importing environmental base data EA Ecology Fish Data Explorer; import_rhs importing River Habitat Survey (RHS) data EA’s Open Data portal; import_wq importing water quality data EA Water Quality Explorer; predict_indices calculating expected scores macroinvertebrate indices using RICT model (FBA 2020); calc_flowstats calc_rfrstats calculating summary statistics describing historical flow conditions; join_he joining datasets; plot_heatmap visualising summarising gaps time series data; plot_hev shiny_hev producing time series plots biology flow data; plot_sitepca summarising environmental characteristics biological sampling sites; plot_rngflows Visualising range flow conditions experienced historically site; model_cv model_logocv performing cross-validation linear mixed-effects models hierarchical generalized additive models; diag_lmer generating variety diagnostic plots mixed-effects regression (lmer) model; plot_predictions visualising time series predictions hydro-ecological model. vignette illustrates typical workflow using selection 20 macroinvertebrate sampling sites Environment Agency’s National Drought Monitoring Network (NDMN). Although package developed macroinvertebrate data mind, functions can used kind biological sampling data.

what: Join Biology Data, Environmental Data, and Expected Indices
title: Vignette
text: Prior joining biology data datasets, advisable remove replicate duplicate samples collected site within year season. following code demonstrates join expected biology metric scores predict_indices observed biology metric scores, using common fields biol_site_id Season. Next environmental base data joined using common field biol_site_id.
code: # remove replicate samples biol_data <- biol_data %>%     distinct(biol_site_id, Year, Season, .keep_all = TRUE) # join expected and observed biology metric scores, by biol_site_id and Season biol_all <- dplyr::left_join(biol_data, predict_data, by = c("biol_site_id", "Season")) # join ENV data, by biol_site_id biol_all <- dplyr::left_join(biol_all, env_data, by = "biol_site_id")

title: Vignette
text: impute_flow function designed infill missing records daily flow time series one sites (gauging stations) using either interpolation equipercentile method. Imputation missing flow data can improve later estimation flow statistics using calc_flowstats() function aid visualisation hydro-ecological relationships using plot_hev() function. Note, advisable consult hydrologist flow imputation, particularly data contains extensive/lengthy gaps. straight-forward interpolation can completed using ‘linear’ ‘exponential’ method. output dataset long format, similar produced import_flow. output dataset contains ‘imputed’ colunm; flag indicating whether flow value original (0) imputed (1). Additionally, function plots observed imputed flow values site; enabling user validate imputation. Flow interpolation using ‘linear’ method demonstrated : applying ‘equipercentile’ method, optional ‘donor’ argument can specified. ‘donor’ argument must specified data frame format least two columns: first list flow sites requiring imputation, second list paired donor sites. function assumes data flow sites specified within ‘donor’ data table, including paired donor sites, contained within ‘flow_data’ supplied. flow data paired donor stations already included within ‘flow_data’ dataframe, necessary import donor flow data, append existing flow data (can done using bind_rows() function). brevity use existing site donor data.
code: flow_data_imputed <- impute_flow(flow_data, site_col = "flow_site_id", date_col = "date",     flow_col = "flow", method = "linear") # create 'donor' data frame for site with relatively large data gap (F3105) donor_mapping <- data.frame(station = c("F3105"), donor_station = c("029001"))  # get a list of donor sites donorsites <- as.character(unique(donor_mapping$donor_station))  # impute flow data using the equipercentile method flow_data_imputed <- impute_flow(flow_data, site_col = "flow_site_id", date_col = "date",     flow_col = "flow", method = "equipercentile", donor = donor_mapping)

title: Vignette
text: calc_flowstats takes time series measured modelled flows uses user-defined moving window calculate suite long-term time-varying flow statistics flow statistics one sites (stations). function uses win_start, win_width win_step arguments define moving window, divides flow time series sequence time periods. time periods may contiguous, non-contiguous overlapping. sequence time periods continues including present date, even extends beyond period covered input flow dataset, facilitates subsequent joining flow statistics ecology data join_he function. primarily designed work mean daily flows (e.g. produced import_flow), can also applied time series data longer (e.g. monthly) time step. Regardless, data regularly spaced time step used sites. function also requires site, date flow data columns specified order run. default values arguments, “flow_site_id”, “date” “flow” respectively, match column headers outputs import_flow impute_flow functions. defaults allow data functions passed without editing calc_flowstats, however names can changed normal match data supplied. updated version calc_flowstats function. first iteration function, employs fixed 6-monthly spring autumn flow periods, remains available using calc_flowstats_old. calc_flowstats returns list two data frames. first contains suite time-varying flow statistics every 6 month winter/summer period every site. See ?calc_flowstats definitions statistics. second data table contains long-term flow statistics. data arranged long format, following columns: flow_site_id (unique site id); season (S = summer, W = winter, = ); parameter (base flow index (bfi), flow duration curve percentiles (p1 p99), seasonal means standard deviations Q5, Q10, Q20, Q25, Q30, Q50, Q70, Q75, Q80, Q90, Q95 Q99); value (calculated statistic).

See ?model_cv ?model_logocv details. model_cv model_logocv measure performance model different situations, necessarily agree best model. priority able predict response sites calibration dataset, use model_cv; priority able predict response sites calibration dataset, use model_logocv. following example, process simplifying full model guided model_cv, measures predictive performance using Root Mean Square Error (RMSE); lower values indicate better predictions. r set 20 give stable RMSE estimates control used help prevent model convergence issues. Corr  ##  biol_site_id (Intercept) 4.560e-03 0.067529       ##               Q95z_lag0   2.245e-05 0.004738 -1.00 ##  Residual                 1.380e-03 0.037154       ## Number of obs: 164, groups:  biol_site_id, 17 ##  ## Fixed effects: ##               Estimate Std. Error t value ## (Intercept)  1.025e+00  1.666e-02  61.542 ## Q95z_lag0   -1.306e-03  5.761e-03  -0.227 ## Q10z_lag0    4.982e-03  4.595e-03   1.084 ## Q95z_lag1   -1.276e-06  2.701e-03   0.000 ##  ## Correlation of Fixed Effects: ##           (Intr) Q95z_0 Q10z_0 ## Q95z_lag0 -0.146               ## Q10z_lag0 -0.036 -0.701        ## Q95z_lag1 -0.022 -0.095  0.221 ## optimizer (nloptwrap) convergence code: 0 (OK) ## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular') # get RMSE estimate cv_full[1] ## $RMSE ## [1] 0.04104335 # drop random slope model_1 <- model_full <- lme4::lmer(LIFE_F_OE ~ Q95z_lag0 + Q10z_lag0 + Q95z_lag1 + (1 | biol_site_id), data = autumn_data, REML = FALSE)  cv_1 <- model_cv(model = model_1, data = autumn_data, group = "biol_site_id", k = 5, r = 20, control = my_control) # model_1 has a lower RMSE than model_full, so drop Q95z slope cv_1[1] ## $RMSE ## [1] 0.0401557 # drop Q95zLS1 term model_2 <- model_full <- lme4::lmer(LIFE_F_OE ~ Q95z_lag0 + Q10z_lag0 + (1 | biol_site_id), data = autumn_data, REML = FALSE)  cv_2 <- model_cv(model = model_2, data = autumn_data, group = "biol_site_id", k = 5, r = 20, control = my_control) # model_2 has a lower RMSE than model_full, so drop Q95zLS1 cv_2[1] ## $RMSE ## [1] 0.03969886 # drop Q10z term model_3 <- model_full <- lme4::lmer(LIFE_F_OE ~ Q95z_lag0 + (1 | biol_site_id), data = autumn_data, REML = FALSE)  cv_3 <- model_cv(model = model_3, data = autumn_data, group = "biol_site_id", k = 5, r = 20, control = my_control) # model_3 has a lower RMSE than model_2, so drop Q10z cv_3[1] ## $RMSE ## [1] 0.03956555 # no further model simplification possible; model_3 is the final model.

title: Generating a variety of diagnostic plots for a mixed-effects regression (lmer) model — diag_lmer
text: following diagnostic plots produced: Fitted vs observed values (records, faceted). Normal probability plot (records, faceted). Residuals vs fitted (records faceted). Histogram residuals (records) boxplot residuals (faceted). Residuals vs model fixed predictor(s) (records ). displays linear model (red) fixed predictor vs model's residuals. blue line loess-smoothed line. main purpose plot check whether relationship residuals predictor linear.

title: Generating a variety of diagnostic plots for a mixed-effects regression (lmer) model — diag_lmer
code: ## Example 1 # attach(lme4) # sleepstudy$type <- rep(c("A","B","C"),60)  # run model # mod <- lmer(Reaction ~ Days + (Days | Subject), sleepstudy)  # run diagnostic plots - with facet option # diag_lmer(model = mod, data = sleepstudy, facet_by = "Subject", order_by = "mean", order = "ascending", ncol = 4, scales = "fixed", colour_by = "type")  ## Example 2 - without facet option, and saving to png file # diag_lmer(model = mod, data = sleepstudy, facet_by = NULL, order_by = "mean", order = "ascending", ncol = 4, scales = "fixed", colour_by = "type", save = TRUE)

what: Infilling missing records in daily flow time series for one or more sites — impute_flow
title: Infilling missing records in daily flow time series for one or more sites — impute_flow
text: function imputes (infills) missing records daily flow time series one sites (gauging stations) using either interpolation equipercentile  method. Imputation missing flow data can improve later estimation flow statistics using calc_flowstats() function aid visualisation hydro-ecological relationships using plot_hev() function.  Note, although function provides automated tools imputing missing records, advisable consult hydrologist data contains extensive/lengthy gaps, ensure methods results trustworthy.

title: Infilling missing records in daily flow time series for one or more sites — impute_flow

Default = "flow_site_id". Site ids coerced character vector. date_col Name column data containing date flow record. Default = "date".  Dates must "yyyy-mm-dd" format. flow_col Name column data containing measured  flows. Default = "flow". method Imputation method: "linear" (default), "exponential" "equipercentile". donor – tibble data frame least two columns: first list flow sites requiring imputation, second list paired donor sites. Subsequent columns ignored. Default = NULL. used method = "equipercentile".  Note, date ranges donor site flow site interest must overlap minimum 365 records (.e. 1 year).

text: function intended imputing gauged daily flow data ; used impute sub-daily data, designed data coarser time steps (e.g. 10-daily monthly). function offers three imputation methods: linear interpolation, exponential interpolation equipercentile algorithm. default linear method uses linear (straight line) interpolation impute missing flow values. therefore unable infill gaps beginning end time series (flow values remain NA). exponential method assumes flow changes exponentially time, produces imputed values accelerating rate change flow rising limb hydrograph, decelerating rate change descending limb. Specifically, flow day t (Qt) function flow previous day (Qt-1) exponential decay constant (λ): Qt = Qt-1 x e-λ. example, flow time series 3 day gap – 10, NA, NA, NA, 6 – exponential decay constant λ = ln(10/6) / 4 = 0.1277. interpolated value day 2 therefore 10 x e-0.1277 = 8.801, full interpolated time series : 10.000, 8.801, 7.746, 6.817, 6.000. Like linear method, however, unable infill gaps beginning end time series. Furthermore, exponential method fail flow value immediately gap 0 (negative). equipercentile method uses measured flows donor site estimate missing flows target site. Specifically, percentile value donor flow given day assumed equal percentile value target flow. Gaps infilled calculating donor flow percentile values using existing target flow data derive flow equivalent percentile value target site (details see Hughes Smakhtin 1996). donor site used target site can specified user (via donors argument). donors = NULL, function finds site data whose flows strongly correlated (using Spearman’s rank correlation coefficient) target site, uses donor site. Note automated method guarantee donor site identified suitable; indeed, donor site may unsuitable none sites climatologically hydrologically similar target site. mitigate risk poor imputation, function requires paired target donor sites minimum 365 overlapping measured flow records. condition met donor site identified, function provides warning message listing sites affected. interpolation methods benefit simplicity typically perform best used infill relatively short gaps – .e. intervals reasonable assume flows stable changing linearly exponentially time. equipercentile method can better interpolation infilling longer gaps, flows may change abruptly response rainfall events, performance critically dependent suitability donor site. Donor sites hydrologically similar , flows strongly correlated , target site. conditions met, equipercentile method can produce imprecise biased imputed values. suitable donor site used, equipercentile method demonstrated superior many imputation techniques (including catchment area scaling, long-term mean scaling, linear regression methods using single donor site) perform similarly multiple regression using two donor sites (Harvey et al. 2012). function applies just one, chosen method time, default fall-back methods. first method fails infill gaps, function can run second time, different chosen method, try infill remaining gaps, . iterative approach provides flexibility determine sequence methods applied. linear exponential methods can applied single site, equipercentile method requires minimum two sites (site acting donor ). processing data multiple sites, recommended sites flow data span common time period. essential, however, function identifies earliest latest dates (across sites), ‘expands’ output dataset cover dates sites. flow imputed certain date, flow value returned NA.

text: biol_data Data frame tibble containing processed biology data. Must contain following columns: biol_site_id date (date format). flow_stats Data frame tibble containing calculated time-varying flow statistics, site time period win_no (produced calc_flowstats function ). Must contain following columns: flow_site_id, start_date end_date. function joins variables flow_stats, advisable manually drop flow statistics interest applying function. mapping Data frame tibble containing paired biology sites IDs flow site IDs. Must contain columns named biol_site_id flow_site_id. columns must contain NAs. Default = NULL, assumes paired biology flow sites identical ids, mapping required. method Choice method linking biology samples flow statistics antecedent time periods. Using method = "" (default), lag 0 defined biology sample recently finished flow time period; using method = "B", lag 0 defined recently started flow time period. See details. lags Vector lagged flow time periods interest. Values must zero positive, larger values representing longer time lags (.e. increasing time gap flow time period biology sample date). Default = 0. See details. join_type add flow statistics biology sample, choose "add_flows" (default); produces dataset biology metrics (response variables) flow statistics (predictor variables) hydro-ecological modelling. add biology sample data flow statistics time period, choose "add_biol"; produces time series flow statistics associated biological metrics can used, example, assess coverage historical flow conditions using plot_rngflows function.

text: biol_data flow_stats may contain sites listed mapping, sites listed mapping filtered . mapping = NULL, biology site flow sites matching ids paired automatically. calc_flowstats function uses moving window approach calculate time-varying flow statistics  sequence time periods can either: () contiguous (.e. time period followed immediately next one), (ii) non-contiguous (.e. gap one time period next), (iii) -lapping (.e. next time period stats previous one finished). describe antecedent flow conditions prior biology sample, time periods labelled relative date biology sample, lag 0 representing either recently finished (method = "") recently started (method = "B") flow time period. time period immediately prior Lag 0 time period Lag 1 period, period immediately prior Lag 2 period, . example, suppose biology sample dated 15 September 2020 flow statistics available sequence contiguous 1 month periods (one calendar month). Using method = "", Lag 0 period biology sample August 2020 (recently finished time period), Lag 1 period July 2020, Lag 2 period June 2020, . Similarly, using method = "B", Lag 0 period biology sample September 2020 (recently started time period), Lag 1 period August 2020, Lag 2 period July 2020, . second example, suppose biology sample dated 15 September 2020 flow statistics available sequence overlapping 6 month periods (.e. February July 2020, March August 2020, April September 2020, ). Using method = "", Lag 0 period biology sample March August 2020 (recently finished time period), Lag 1 period February July 2020, Lag 2 period January June 2020, . Similarly, using method ="B", Lag 0 period biology sample September 2000 February 2021 (recently started time period), Lag 1 period 1 August 2000 January 2021, Lag 2 period July December 2020, . Note using join_type = "add_biol", flow period becomes replicated 2+ biology samples within . avoid happening, summarise (e.g. average) replicate biology samples within time window applying join_he. amend ggplot elements, such as the title a[[1]] + labs(title = "this adds a new title to the plot")  # view tibble of missing flow values by date (variable x) a[[2]] #> # A tibble: 3,652 × 4 #>    x          missing total prop_missing #>    <fct>        <int> <int>        <dbl> #>  1 2010-01-01       0    20            0 #>  2 2010-01-02       0    20            0 #>  3 2010-01-03       0    20            0 #>  4 2010-01-04       0    20            0 #>  5 2010-01-05       0    20            0 #>  6 2010-01-06       0    20            0 #>  7 2010-01-07       0    20            0 #>  8 2010-01-08       0    20            0 #>  9 2010-01-09       0    20            0 #> 10 2010-01-10       0    20            0 #> # ℹ 3,642 more rows # view tibble of missing flow values by site (variable y) a[[3]] #> # A tibble: 20 × 7 #>    y      missing total prop_missing number_of_gaps smallest_gap biggest_gap #>    <chr>    <int> <int>        <dbl>          <int>        <int>       <int> #>  1 029001       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #>  2 029003       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #>  3 030017       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #>  4 031031       4  3652     0.00110               2            1           3 #>  5 032806       1  3652     0.000274              1            1           1 #>  6 033022       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #>  7 033044       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #>  8 033051       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #>  9 034003       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 10 034014       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 11 034206       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 12 035002       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 13 035004       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 14 037005       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 15 2859TH       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 16 4175         0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 17 4790TH       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 18 5420TH       0  3652     0                    NA           NA          NA #> 19 F3105       76  3652     0.0208                5            2          62 #> 20 U33093     245  3652     0.0671                2           47         198  # setting dual = TRUE adds a marginal histogram displaying % missingness a <- plot_heatmap(data = df, x = "date", y = "flow_site_id", fill = "flow", limits = TRUE, dual = TRUE) #> Warning: limits set to TRUE, dataset being trimmed to a maximum of the first 30 unique x values and first 20 unique y values, no effect if less than 30 x and 20 y occur within the dataset. If trimming is not wanted set 'limits' = FALSE   # to plot this device, the code needed is slightly different: gridExtra::grid.arrange(a[[1]])   # Presence-absence heatmap plot, showing whether or not flow was measured on each date at each site. Using dual=TRUE includes a marginal barchart to visualise, for each site, the proportion of days that do not have a daily flow value.  df$presence <- "1" df$presence[is.na(df$flow)]<- NA a <- plot_heatmap(data = df, x = "date", y = "flow_site_id", fill = "presence", dual = TRUE)  gridExtra::grid.arrange(a[[1]])   # Identifying missing variables. # If certain dates are completely missing from an input dataset, they will not show in the heatmap plot unless they are explicitly added as missing values. In this example we expand the x time step to include missing days and re-plot to demonstrate how this can be accounted for. If not using some form of date, a list of unique options of x and or y will need to be specified as a vector similar to that produced by unique(df$sites).  # artificially remove some specific days from the data temp1 <- df[!df$date %in% lubridate::date(c("2000-02-07", "2000-02-08", "2000-12-12", "2001-09-19")),]  # use expand.grid() to re-create the missing days new <- expand.grid(date = seq(min(temp1$date, na.rm=TRUE), max(temp1$date, na.rm=TRUE), 1), flow_site_id = unique(temp1$flow_site_id))  # join the flow data to the new expanded grid to generate NA flow values on the four missing days temp <- dplyr::full_join(temp1, new, by=c("date","flow_site_id")) temp[temp$date %in% lubridate::date(c("2000-02-07","2000-02-08", "2000-12-12","2001-09-19")),] #> # A tibble: 0 × 6 #> # ℹ 6 variables: input <chr>, flow_site_id <chr>, date <date>, flow <dbl>, #> #   quality <chr>, presence <chr> temp <- temp[order(temp$date),]  # heatmap showing missing daily flow records (zoom in RStudio to see all four missing days) a <- plot_heatmap(data = temp, x = "date", y = "flow_site_id", fill = "flow") a[[1]]   rm(list= c("new","temp", "temp1"))  # Calculate and then plot monthly mean flows  # artificially remove some data temp <- df temp$flow[temp$date %in% lubridate::date(c("2000-02-07","2000-02-08","2000-12-12","2001-09-19"))] <- NA temp$flow[temp$flow_site_id %in% c("SS60F015","029004") & temp$date %in% lubridate::date(c("2000-01-02","2001-06-22","2001-10-12"))] <- NA  # calculate monthly mean flows temp$month <- lubridate::month(df$date) temp$year <- lubridate::year(df$date) temp$yy_mm <- paste(temp$year, temp$month, sep = "-") temp1 <- temp %>% dplyr::group_by(month, year, yy_mm, flow_site_id) %>% dplyr::summarise(across(.cols= "flow",  list(mean = ~mean(flow, na.rm = TRUE),       missing = ~length(which(is.na(flow))),       total = ~length(flow),       perc_missing = ~(length(which(is.na(flow)))/length(flow))*100),  .names = "{.fn}")) #> `summarise()` has grouped output by 'month', 'year', 'yy_mm'. You can override #> using the `.groups` argument. temp1$yy_mm <- paste(temp1$year,temp1$month,sep="_")  # heatmap showing monthly mean flows a <- plot_heatmap(data = temp1, x = "yy_mm", y = "flow_site_id", fill = "mean",dual = TRUE)  gridExtra::grid.arrange(a[[1]])   # heatmap showing percentage completeness of the daily flow data in each month a <- plot_heatmap(data = temp1, x = "yy_mm", y = "flow_site_id", fill = "perc_missing") a[[1]]   # every month has a mean flow, so no missing records at this time step a[[3]] #> # A tibble: 20 × 7 #>    y      missing total prop_missing number_of_gaps smallest_gap biggest_gap #>    <chr>    <int> <int>        <dbl>          <int>        <int>       <int> #>  1 029001       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  2 029003       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  3 030017       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  4 031031       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  5 032806       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  6 033022       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  7 033044       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  8 033051       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #>  9 034003       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 10 034014       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 11 034206       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 12 035002       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 13 035004       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 14 037005       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 15 2859TH       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 16 4175         0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 17 4790TH       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 18 5420TH       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 19 F3105        0   120            0             NA           NA          NA #> 20 U33093       0   120            0             NA           NA          NA  rm(list=c("temp","temp1"))

text: data data frame site-level environmental characteristics produced import_env. vars list least three continuous environmental variables 'data'. eigenvectors Logical option add eigenvectors PCA plot. Default = FALSE. label_by Optional variable label points (e.g. site ID). Default = NULL. colour_by Optional variable colour points (e.g. catchment). title: Summarising environmental characteristics of biological sampling sites — plot_sitepca
text: Depending 'plotly' argument, either ggplot plotly plot displaying   sites 2D space show site similarity identify potential outliers.

title: Summarising environmental characteristics of biological sampling sites — plot_sitepca
text: environmental variables listed 'vars' must numeric, complete; sites missing data excluded analysis. variables automatically centered zero scaled unit variance prior analysis (see ?stats::prcomp details). plot_sitepca function performs PCA using stats::prcomp() plots z-scores first two principal components. Using label_by exchanges point defining variable, site ID, can help identifying outliers. Setting eigenvectors = TRUE add arrows plot indicate direction strength correlation environmental variables principal components. Longer arrows indicate stronger correlations. eigenvectors allow axes interpreted environmental gradients.

what: Calculating expected scores for macroinvertebrate indices using the RICT2 model — predict_indices
title: Calculating expected scores for macroinvertebrate indices using the RICT2 model — predict_indices
text: predict_indices function mirrors functionality RICT model available MS Azure platform (https://gallery.azure.ai/Experiment/RICT-package-2). Specifically, uses  environmental (ENV) data Ecology Data Explorer generate expected scores minimally impacted reference conditions 80 indices, plus probabilities RIVPACS end-groups. prediction functionality applies 'rict_predict()' function AquaMetrics RICT package (https://github.com/aquaMetrics/rict). classification undertaken.

text: env_data data frame tibble containing site-level environmental data Environment Agency Ecology Data Explorer format (produced import_env function). file_format Format env_data supplied: "EDE" - environmental data formatted downloaded EA's Ecology Data Explorer; "RICT" - environmental data RICT template format. save Specifies whether expected indices data saved rds file (future use); Default = TRUE. save_dir Path folder expected indices data saved; Default = Current working directory. all_indices Boolean. TRUE - Return indices output (default); FALSE - returns WHPT indices (arguement passed rict::rict_predict).
